INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'd1059994-03cf-4338-8c5e-322a41ad4ea6',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Spring Boot Project Structure — MVC Layers vs Vertical Slices$escape$,
  $escape$Classic Spring Boot projects default to horizontal layering: `controller/`, `service/`, `repository/` packages at the root. This works for small apps but breaks down fast — adding a `Payment` feature means touching four separate packages, and `PaymentController` ends up importing `UserService` because the boundaries were never enforced.

Vertical slice architecture flips this: each feature owns its full stack. A `payment/` package contains `PaymentController`, `PaymentService`, `PaymentRepository`, and its DTOs. Spring's component scanning works seamlessly with this — `@ComponentScan` picks up `@Service`, `@Repository`, and `@RestController` regardless of depth.

The key Spring Boot idiom here is using `@SpringBootApplication` at the root with no explicit `scanBasePackages`, then letting feature folders self-contain their beans. For cross-cutting concerns (auth, auditing), `@Aspect` beans in a `common/` or `shared/` package still get picked up automatically.

Vertical slices align naturally with Spring Modulith's `@ApplicationModule` boundaries — if you ever want formal module enforcement or event-driven decoupling via `ApplicationEventPublisher`, your folder structure is already correct.$escape$,
  $escape$// Vertical slice layout for a Payment feature
com.example.app
├── payment
│   ├── PaymentController.java   // @RestController
│   ├── PaymentService.java      // @Service
│   ├── PaymentRepository.java   // @Repository
│   └── PaymentRequest.java      // DTO / record
├── user
│   ├── UserController.java
│   ├── UserService.java
│   └── UserRepository.java
└── shared
    └── GlobalExceptionHandler.java  // @ControllerAdvice$escape$,
  $escape$bash$escape$,
