INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'de62d6a4-c91f-4811-86d0-f4264fe4fffe',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Spring Boot DI — Constructor Injection vs Field Injection and the Testability Trap$escape$,
  $escape$Spring Boot's IoC container manages beans through component scanning (@Component, @Service, @Repository) and explicit @Bean factory methods inside @Configuration classes. The critical distinction is how dependencies reach those beans.

Field injection (@Autowired on a private field) couples your class to Spring's runtime context — you can't instantiate it with `new` in a unit test without reflection hacks or a full ApplicationContext. Constructor injection flips this entirely: dependencies become explicit constructor parameters, making your class a plain Kotlin/Java object any test can instantiate directly.

Spring Boot 2.x+ auto-wires single-constructor beans with zero @Autowired boilerplate. Use @SpringBootTest for integration tests that need the full context, and plain unit tests for isolated business logic — no context startup cost. For non-trivial wiring, @Configuration + @Bean gives compile-time visibility that @Autowired scattered across classes cannot.

Manual wiring (`new OrderService(new PaymentClient())`) belongs exclusively at the test layer. In production code, hand-wiring bypasses lifecycle callbacks (@PostConstruct, @PreDestroy) and Spring's scope management (@Scope("prototype")), silently breaking intended behavior.$escape$,
  $escape$@Service
class OrderService(
    private val paymentClient: PaymentClient,
    private val orderRepo: OrderRepository
) {
    fun place(order: Order): Order =
        orderRepo.save(order.also { paymentClient.charge(it) })
}

// Unit test — zero Spring context, no @SpringBootTest overhead
class OrderServiceTest {
    private val paymentClient = mockk<PaymentClient>()
    private val orderRepo = mockk<OrderRepository>()
    private val sut = OrderService(paymentClient, orderRepo)
}$escape$,
  $escape$kotlin$escape$,
