INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '89f3d1e6-71e1-4cbd-a616-7fa595873480',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Spring Boot API Versioning — URI, Header, and OpenAPI Done Right$escape$,
  $escape$Spring Boot gives you three practical versioning strategies: URI-based (`/api/v1/users`), request header (`X-API-Version: 1`), or `Accept` header content negotiation (`application/vnd.app.v1+json`). URI versioning is the most cache-friendly and easiest to debug — map it with `@RequestMapping("/api/v1")` on a dedicated controller class per version. For header-based routing, use a `RequestMappingHandlerMapping` bean with a custom condition.

SpringDoc OpenAPI 2.x (for Spring Boot 3) auto-generates `/v3/api-docs` and Swagger UI. Annotate controllers with `@Tag(name = "Users v1")` and operations with `@Operation(summary = "...")`. To expose separate specs per version, configure multiple `GroupedOpenApi` beans — one per version prefix.

Avoid mixing versions in the same controller. Keep `V1UserController` and `V2UserController` as separate classes sharing a common service layer. Deprecate old endpoints with `@Operation(deprecated = true)` so Swagger UI renders the strikethrough visually. Use `@Schema(description = "...")` on DTOs to generate accurate OpenAPI models without manual spec files.$escape$,
  $escape$@Configuration
public class OpenApiConfig {

    @Bean
    public GroupedOpenApi v1Api() {
        return GroupedOpenApi.builder()
                .group("v1")
                .pathsToMatch("/api/v1/**")
                .build();
    }

    @Bean
    public GroupedOpenApi v2Api() {
        return GroupedOpenApi.builder()
                .group("v2")
                .pathsToMatch("/api/v2/**")
                .build();
    }
}$escape$,
  $escape$kotlin$escape$,
