INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'eb1e11d2-74a5-46e0-8864-3b9808e56f67',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Spring Boot Configuration — Env Vars, @ConfigurationProperties, and Secrets Done Right$escape$,
  $escape$Spring Boot's externalized configuration follows a strict property source precedence: environment variables override `application.yml`, which overrides defaults. For structured config, prefer `@ConfigurationProperties` over `@Value` — it gives you type safety, validation, and IDE autocomplete.

Annotate a record or class with `@ConfigurationProperties(prefix = "app")` and register it via `@EnableConfigurationProperties` or by marking it `@Component`. Add `spring-boot-configuration-processor` to your build for annotation processing.

For secrets, never hardcode in `application.yml`. Use environment variable substitution (`${DB_PASSWORD}`) or integrate Spring Cloud Vault / AWS Secrets Manager via the corresponding Spring Cloud starter. In production on Kubernetes, inject secrets as env vars from a `Secret` object — Spring Boot picks them up automatically through its `SystemEnvironmentPropertySource`.

For profile-specific overrides, use `application-prod.yml` activated via `SPRING_PROFILES_ACTIVE=prod`. Use `@Validated` with JSR-380 annotations (`@NotNull`, `@Min`) on your `@ConfigurationProperties` class to fail fast at startup if required config is missing.$escape$,
  $escape$@ConfigurationProperties(prefix = "app.database")
@Validated
public record DatabaseProperties(
    @NotBlank String url,
    @NotBlank String username,
    @NotBlank String password,
    @Min(1) @Max(50) int poolSize
) {}

// application.yml
// app:
//   database:
//     url: ${DB_URL}
//     username: ${DB_USER}
//     password: ${DB_PASSWORD}
//     pool-size: 10$escape$,
  $escape$kotlin$escape$,
