INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'fa5c971a-8807-416d-96a0-b499df33c00b',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Spring Boot's Batteries-Included Superpowers: Auto-Config, Actuator, and OpenAPI in Minutes$escape$,
  $escape$Spring Boot's 'batteries-included' philosophy means you rarely wire infrastructure by hand. Three features stand out for daily backend work.

**Auto-Configuration** scans your classpath and configures beans automatically — add `spring-boot-starter-data-jpa` and you get a `DataSource`, `EntityManagerFactory`, and transaction manager wired up without a single `@Bean` definition.

**Spring Boot Actuator** exposes production-ready endpoints (`/actuator/health`, `/actuator/metrics`, `/actuator/env`) the moment you add the dependency. Pair it with Micrometer and Prometheus scrapes your app with zero instrumentation code.

**SpringDoc OpenAPI** (the modern replacement for Springfox) auto-generates a Swagger UI and `openapi.json` by scanning your `@RestController` classes. Annotate with `@Operation` and `@Schema` for richer docs, but the baseline works out of the box.

The key insight: Spring Boot's starters compose — each starter pulls in auto-configuration classes registered in `META-INF/spring/org.springframework.boot.autoconfigure.AutoConfiguration.imports`. You can inspect exactly what was configured via `/actuator/conditions`.$escape$,
  $escape$// build.gradle — three starters, three batteries included
implementation 'org.springframework.boot:spring-boot-starter-data-jpa'
implementation 'org.springframework.boot:spring-boot-starter-actuator'
implementation 'org.springdoc:springdoc-openapi-starter-webmvc-ui:2.5.0'

// application.yml
management:
  endpoints:
    web:
      exposure:
        include: health,metrics,conditions
springdoc:
  api-docs:
    path: /api-docs
  swagger-ui:
    path: /swagger-ui.html

// That's it — hit /swagger-ui.html and /actuator/conditions to see the magic$escape$,
  $escape$kotlin$escape$,
